ML There are five main types of agents, categorized by their level of intelligence and complexity:  Simple Reflex Agents: These are the most basic. They act only on the basis of the current perception, ignoring history. They use "If-Condition-Then-Action" rules.  Example: A thermostat (If temp < 20°C, then Turn On heater).  Model-Based Reflex Agents: These handle partially observable environments by maintaining an internal state (a model of the world) to keep track of parts of the world they cannot see right now.  Example: A robot vacuum that remembers which rooms it has already cleaned.  Goal-Based Agents: These agents act to achieve a specific destination or state. They don't just react; they plan a sequence of actions to reach a goal.  Example: A GPS navigation system finding the shortest path to your house.  Utility-Based Agents: These are "extra-smart" goal-based agents. They don't just want to reach a goal; they want to reach it in the best way possible (maximizing "utility" like speed, safety, or cost).  Example: A ride-sharing app choosing a route that balances distance, traffic, and fuel efficiency.  Learning Agents: These can operate in unknown environments and become more competent over time by learning from their experiences. They have a "critic" that gives feedback on performance.  Example: A self-driving car that improves its braking based on road conditions over months of driving.
